First, let's find A x B and B ⋃ C.

A x B = {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4)}

B ⋃ C = {2, 3, 4}

Now, let's find (A x B) ⋃ C and A x (B ⋃ C).

(A x B) ⋃ C = {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4)} ⋃ {2, 3, 4} = {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), 2, 3, 4}

A x (B ⋃ C) = {1, 2} x {2, 3, 4} = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4)}

As we can see, (A x B) ⋃ C ≠ A x (B ⋃ C) because their elements are not the same. The union of the two sets is not equal.
